$2\int_{0}^{\pi^{\frac{1}{n}}}\left(\frac{\sin\left(x^{n}\right)}{x^{n}}\right)dx$
aka
$\int_{-\pi^{\frac{1}{n}}}^{\pi^{\frac{1}{n}}}\left(\frac{\sin\left(x^{n}\right)}{x^{n}}\right)dx$
has an interesting value at n=1/2 $(4)$
which is an integer
This converges if $x^n$ is viewed as $a$
and thus one gets $2\int_{0}^{\pi^{\frac{1}{n}}}\left(\frac{\sin\left({a}\right)}{a}\right)dx$
which of course converges at infinity

similar integral $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \left(\frac{\sin\left(x^{n}\right)}{x^{n}}\right) dx$ evaluates indefinitely to $\dfrac{\operatorname{\Gamma}\left(-\frac{n-1}{n},-\mathrm{i}\left(x+1\right)^n\right)-\left(-1\right)^\frac{n-1}{n}\operatorname{\Gamma}\left(-\frac{n-1}{n},\mathrm{i}\left(x+1\right)^n\right)}{2\left(-\mathrm{i}\right)^\frac{1}{n}n}$ 

For example when n = 3 the function evaluates to 
$\dfrac{\mathrm{i}\left(\operatorname{\Gamma}\left(-\frac{2}{3},\mathrm{i}x^3\right)-\operatorname{\Gamma}\left(-\frac{2}{3},-\mathrm{i}x^3\right)\right)}{6}$ indefinitely


The aforementioned calculations are based on Wolfram Alpha, the most reputable source in mathematics




Thanks to Nathan van Brant, he has calculated the general formula of $\int_{0}^{\infty} \left(\frac{\sin\left(x^{n}\right)}{x^{n}}\right) dx$
he deserves full credit here
anycase
$\int_{0}^{\infty} \left(\frac{\sin\left(x^{n}\right)}{x^{n}}\right) dx$ = $sin(\frac{\mathrm{\pi } }{\mathrm{} 2} \frac{\mathrm{1-n} }{\mathrm{} n})\frac{\mathrm{-n } }{\mathrm{} n-1}  \Gamma (\frac{\mathrm{1-n} }{\mathrm{}n}) = sin(\frac{\mathrm{\pi } }{\mathrm{} 2}( \frac{\mathrm{1} }{\mathrm{} n}-1))\frac{\mathrm{-n } }{\mathrm{} n-1} (\frac{\mathrm{1} }{\mathrm{}n}!)$

